HEGzX\n  annotations:\n    github.com/project-slug: backstage/backstage\n    backstage.io/techdocs-ref: dir:.\n    lighthouse.com/website-url: https://backstage.io\n[...]\nspec:\n  type: library\n  owner: CNCF\n  lifecycle: production\n\n```\n\n---\n\nTitle: docs/features/software-catalog/descriptor-format.md at master · backstage/backstage\nURL: https://github.com/backstage/backstage/blob/master/docs/features/software-catalog/descriptor-format.md\nPublished: N/A\nAuthor: N/A\nHighlights:\nAlthough it's possible to name catalog entity descriptor files however you wish,\nwe recommend that you name them `catalog-info.yaml`.\n[...]\n```yaml\napiVersion: backstage.io/v1alpha1\nkind: Component\nmetadata:\n  name: artist-web\n  description: The place to be, for great artists\n  labels:\n    example.com/custom: custom_label_value\n  annotations:\n    example.com/service-discovery: artistweb\n    circleci.com/project-slug: github/example-org/artist-website\n  tags:\n    - java\n  links:\n    - url: https://admin.example-org.com\n      title: Admin Dashboard\n      icon: dashboard\n      type: admin-dashboard\n[...]\nspec:\n  type: website\n  lifecycle: production\n  owner: artist-relations-team\n  system: public-websites\n[...]\n:/tmp/catalog-info.yaml\",\n      \"\n[...]\n.com/\n[...]\n\",\n      \"circle\n[...]\nslug\": \"github/example-org/\n[...]\n},\n    \"\n[...]\n\": [\n      {\n        \"\n[...]\n.example-org.com\",\n        \"title\": \"Admin Dashboard\",\n        \"icon\": \"dashboard\",\n        \"type\": \"admin-\n[...]\n\"\n      }\n    ],\n    \"tags\": [\"java\"],\n    \"name\": \"artist-\n[...]\n\",\n    \"uid\": \"2\n[...]\n},\n  \"spec\": {\n    \"\n[...]\n\": \"production\",\n    \"owner\": \"artist-\n[...]\n-team\",\n    \"type\": \"website\",\n    \"system\": \"public-websites\"\n  }\n}\n[...]\nThe root fields `apiVersion`, `kind`, `metadata`, and `spec` are part of the\n_envelope_, defining the overall structure of all kinds of entity. Likewise,\nsome metadata fields like `name`, `labels`, and `annotations` are of special\nsignificance and have reserved purposes and distinct shapes.\n[...]\n### `metadata` [required]\n[...]\n### `spec` [varies]\n[...]\n### `tags` [optional]\n[...]\n## Kind: Component\n[...]\n### `spec.type` [required]\n[...]\n### `spec.lifecycle` [required]\n[...]\n### `spec.owner` [required]\n[...]\n### `spec.system` [optional]\n[...]\n### `spec.lifecycle` [required]\n[...]\n### `spec.owner` [required]\n[...]\n### `spec.system` [optional]\n[...]\n### `spec.owner` [required\n[...]\n## Kind: System\n[...]\n### `spec.owner` [required]\n[...]\n### `spec.owner\n\n---\n\nTitle: Viewing the Catalog | Backstage Software Catalog and Developer Platform\nURL: https://backstage.io/docs/getting-started/viewing-catalog\nPublished: N/A\nAuthor: N/A\nHighlights:\ncomponents that cooperate\n[...]\nperform a function\n[...]\nseveral public APIs.\n[...]\nhides the resources and private APIs between the components from the consumer.\n[...]\n- `Domains`- A collection\n[...]\n- `Kind`- Component\n- `Type`- all\n- `Owner`- Owned\n- `Lifecycle`- list of lifecycle values of entities in the Catalog\n- `Processing Status`- normal\n- `Namespace`- The ID of a namespace to which the entity belongs\n[...]\nFor each kind of entity, a set of columns display information regarding the entity. For example, the default set of information for a`Component` is:\n[...]\n`Lifecycle`\n[...]\n- `experimental`- an experiment or early, non-production component, signaling that users may not prefer to consume it over other more established components, or that there are low or no reliability guarantees\n- `production`- an established, owned, maintained component\n- `deprecated`- a component that is at the end of its lifecycle, and may disappear at a later point in time\n[...]\n- `Actions`- see Catalog Actions\n- View - View the`catalog-info.yaml` file that defines the entity.\n- Edit - Edit the`catalog-info.yaml` file that defines the entity. See Updating a Component\n- Star - Designate the entity as a favorite. You can filter the catalog for starred entities.\n[...]\nSelecting an entity in the main panel displays details of the entity. The type of details depends on the type of entity. For example, selecting a Component, such as`example-website`, displays the following details:\n[...]\n- `About`- Metadata for the entity, such as description, owner, tags, and domain.\n- `Relations`- see Viewing entity relationships\n- `Links`- any links associated with the entity\n- `Has subcomponents`- An entity reference to another component of which the component is a part\n[...]\nSelecting a System, such as`examples`, displays`About`,`Relations`, and`Links` similar to a Component, but it also includes`Has components`,`APIs` and`Has Resources`.","metadata":{"truncated":false},"title":"","time":{"start":1777014317364,"end":1777014318744},"attachments":[]},"id":"prt_dbe4ea12f001cKCQ0i9xwfSxvS","sessionID":"ses_241d9f7b3ffeMqi0Lc2w61CcA3","messageID":"msg_dbe4e73a2001uTqJa28o1GX35E"}}
{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1777014318838,"sessionID":"ses_241d9f7b3ffeMqi0Lc2w61CcA3","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"websearch_web_search_exa","callID":"call_9mGQxDx7hi1eJROFhZ2JnYkt","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"numResults":5,"query":"Nx project.json official docs project configuration tags projectType targets metadata"},"output":"Title: Project Configuration - Nx\nURL: https://nx.dev/docs/reference/project-configuration\nPublished: N/A\nAuthor: N/A\nHighlights:\n\"options\": {\n            \"command\": \"vite dev\",\n            \"continuous\": true\n          },\n          \"\n[...]\n\": {\n            \"technologies\": [\"vite\"]\n          }\n        },\n[...]\n\"build\": {\n          \"executor\": \"nx:run-commands\",\n          \"inputs\": [\"production\", \"^production\"],\n          \"outputs\": [\"{project\n[...]\ndist\"],\n          \"options\": {\n            \"\n[...]\nbuild\"\n          },\n[...]\n{\n            \"technologies\": [\"\n[...]\n\"]\n          }\n        }\n      }\n    }\n[...]\n.config.ts\", \"@nx/\n[...]\n\": [\"packages/\n[...]\n.config.ts\", \"@nx/\n[...]\n\": [\"packages/\n[...]\nIf you need to edit your project settings or modify an inferred task, you can do so in either `package.json` or `project.json` files. The examples on this page show both styles. Nx merges the two files to get each project's configuration. The full machine readable schema is available on GitHub.\n[...]\nBoth `package.json` and `project.json` can be used to configure Nx targets, and both support the same configuration options including executors:\n[...]\n- package.json: Use the `\"nx\"` property to define targets with executors, options, and other Nx-specific configuration\n- project.json: A dedicated Nx configuration file that keeps your `package.json` focused on package metadata\n[...]\n// project.json\n{\n  \"root\": \"libs/mylib/\",\n  \"sourceRoot\": \"libs/mylib/src\",\n  \"projectType\": \"library\",\n  \"tags\": [\"scope:myteam\"],\n  \"i