{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1777014319146,"sessionID":"ses_241d9f7b3ffeMqi0Lc2w61CcA3","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"websearch_web_search_exa","callID":"call_80WIZMY0BdVsaCXCHSlnFOx8","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"numResults":5,"query":"Kubernetes labels selectors official docs recommended labels app.kubernetes.io name instance version component part-of managed-by"},"output":"Title: Labels and Selectors - Kubernetes\nURL: https://kubernetes.io/docs/concepts/overview/working-with-objects/labels/\nPublished: 2026-03-15T05:57:54.000Z\nAuthor: N/A\nHighlights:\nLabels are key/value pairs. Valid label keys have two segments: an optional prefix and name, separated by a slash (`/`). The name segment is required and must be 63 characters or less, beginning and ending with an alphanumeric character (`[a-z0-9A-Z]`) with dashes (`-`), underscores (`_`), dots (`.`), and alphanumerics between. The prefix is optional. If specified, the prefix must be a DNS subdomain: a series of DNS labels separated by dots (`.`), not longer than 253 characters in total, followed by a slash (`/`).\n[...]\nThe`kubernetes.io/` and`k8s.io/` prefixes are reserved for Kubernetes core components.\n[...]\n## Label selectors\n[...]\nVia a label selector, the client/user can identify a set of objects. The label selector is the core grouping primitive in Kubernetes.\n[...]\nThe API currently supports two types of selectors: equality-based and set-based. A label selector can be made of multiple requirements which are comma-separated. In the case of multiple requirements, all must be satisfied so the comma separator acts as a logical AND (`&&`) operator.\n[...]\nIn the following examples, the`app` label is included for convenience in manual queries and simple CLI usage. The`app.kubernetes.io/name` label follows the recommended Kubernetes labeling conventions and is better suited for tooling and automation.\n[...]\nThe frontend could carry the following labels:\n[...]\n```\nlabels:\n  app: guestbook\n  app.kubernetes.io/name: guestbook\n  tier: frontend\n[...]\nthe Redis master and replica would have different`tier` labels, and perhaps even an additional`role` label:\n[...]\n```\nlabels:\n  app: guestbook\n  app.kubernetes.io/name: guestbook\n  tier: backend\n  role: master\n[...]\n```\nlabels:\n  app: guestbook\n  app.kubernetes.io/name: guestbook\n  tier: backend\n  role: replica\n[...]\n- Learn how to\n[...]\nnode\n- Find Well-known\n[...]\n, Annotations and Taints\n- See Recommended\n[...]\n- Enforce Pod Security Standards with Namespace Labels\n- Read a blog on Writing a Controller for Pod Labels\n\n---\n\nTitle: Well-Known Labels, Annotations and Taints | Kubernetes\nURL: https://kubernetes.io/docs/reference/kubernetes-api/labels-annotations-taints\nPublished: 2026-03-05T12:41:55.000Z\nAuthor: N/A\nHighlights:\nKubernetes reserves all labels, annotations and taints in the`kubernetes.io` and`k8s.io` namespaces.\n[...]\n### app.kubernetes.io/component\n[...]\nOne of the recommended labels.\n[...]\n: All Objects (typically\n[...]\n### app.kubernetes.io/instance\n[...]\nType: Label\n[...]\nUsed on: All Objects (typically used on workload resources).\n[...]\nA unique name\n[...]\n. To assign a non-unique name, use app.kubernetes.io/name.\n[...]\nOne of the recommended labels.\n[...]\n### app.kubernetes.io/managed-by\n[...]\nType: Label\n[...]\nOne of the recommended labels.\n[...]\n### app.kubernetes.io/name\n[...]\nType: Label\n[...]\nAll Objects (\n[...]\non workload resources).\n[...]\nOne of the recommended labels.\n[...]\n### app.kubernetes.io/part-of\n[...]\nType: Label\n[...]\non: All Objects (\n[...]\nOne of the recommended labels.\n[...]\n### app.kubernetes.io/version\n[...]\nType: Label\n[...]\n:`app.kubernetes.io\n[...]\n5.7.21\"`\n[...]\nUsed on: All Objects (typically used on workload resources).\n[...]\nversion of the application.\n[...]\nOne of the recommended labels.\n[...]\n``````\nkubectl label nodes <node-\n[...]\nkubernetes.io/exclude\n[...]\n-load-balancers=true\n[...]\n``````\n    kubectl.kubernetes.io/last-applied-configuration: >\n      {\"apiVersion\":\"apps/v1\",\"kind\":\"Deployment\",\"metadata\":{\"annotations\":{},\"name\":\"example\",\"namespace\":\"default\"},\"spec\":{\"selector\":{\"matchLabels\":{\"app.kubernetes.io/name\":foo}},\"template\":{\"metadata\":{\"labels\":{\"app.kubernetes.io/name\":\"foo\"}},\"spec\":{\"containers\":[{\"image\":\"container-registry.example/foo-bar:1.42\",\"name\":\"foo-bar\",\"ports\":[{\"containerPort\":42}]}]}}}}\n\n---\n\nTitle: Concepts | Kubernetes\nURL: https://kubernetes.io/docs/concepts/_print\nPublished: 2020-06-22T22:01:16.000Z\nAuthor: N/A\nHighlights:\nIn the following examples, the`app` label is included for convenience in manual queries and simple CLI usage. The`app.kubernetes.io/name` label follows the recommended Kubernetes labeling conventions and is better suited for tooling and automation.\n[...]\n.io`. Labels\n[...]\na prefix are private to users.\n[...]\nshared prefix ensures that shared labels do not interfere with custom user labels\n[...]\n| Key | Description | Example | Type |\n| --- | --- | --- | --- |\n| `app.kubernetes.io/name` | The name of the application | `mysql` | string |\n| `app.kubernetes.io/instance` | A unique name identifying the instance of an application | `mysql-abcxyz` | string |\n| `app.kubernetes.io/version` | The current version of the application (e.g., a SemVer 1.0, revision hash, etc.) | `5.7.21` | string |\n| `app.kubernetes.io/component` | The component within the architecture | `database` | string |\n| `app.kubernetes.io/part-of` | The name of a higher level application this one is part of | `wordpress` | string |\n| `app.kubernetes.io/managed-by` | The tool being used to manage the operation of an application | `Helm` | string |\n[...]\n# This is an excerpt\napiVersion: apps/v1\nkind: StatefulSet\n[...]\nmetadata:\n  labels:\n[...]\n.kubernetes.io\n[...]\n.kubernetes.io/version: \"\n[...]\n-by:\n[...]\nThe name of an application and the instance name are recorded separately. For example, WordPress has a`app.kubernetes.io/name` of`wordpress` while it has an instance name, represented as`app.kubernetes.io/instance` with a value of`wordpress-abcxyz`. This enables the application and instance of the application to be identifiable. Every instance of an application must have a unique name.\n[...]\n/v1\n[...]\nmetadata:\n[...]\n:\n    app.kubernetes.io/name: wordpress\n    app.kubernetes.io/instance: wordpress-abcxyz\n    app.kubernetes.io/\n[...]\n: \"4.9.4\"\n    app.kubernetes.io/managed-by: Helm\n    app.kubernetes.io/component: server\n    app.kubernetes.io/\n[...]\n-of: wordpress\n\n---\n\nTitle: Recommended Labels | Kubernetes\nURL: https://kubernetes.io/docs/concepts/overview/working-with-objects/common-labels/\nPublished: 2024-04-25T00:16:00.000Z\nAuthor: N/A\nHighlights:\nShared labels and annotations share a common prefix:`app.kubernetes.io`. Labels without a prefix are private to users. The shared prefix ensures that shared labels do not interfere with custom user labels.\n[...]\n| Key | Description | Example | Type |\n| --- | --- | --- | --- |\n| `app.kubernetes.io/name` | The name of the application | `mysql` | string |\n| `app.kubernetes.io/instance` | A unique name identifying the instance of an application | `mysql-abcxyz` | string |\n| `app.kubernetes.io/version` | The current version of the application (e.g., a SemVer 1.0, revision hash, etc.) | `5.7.21` | string |\n| `app.kubernetes.io/component` | The component within the architecture | `database` | string |\n| `app.kubernetes.io/part-of` | The name of a higher level application this one is part of | `wordpress` | string |\n| `app.kubernetes.io/managed-by` | The tool being used to manage the operation of an application | `Helm` | string |\n[...]\nThe name of an application and the instance name are recorded separately. For example, WordPress has a`app.kubernetes.io/name` of`wordpress` while it has an instance name, represented as`app.kubernetes.io/instance` with a value of`wordpress-abcxyz`. This enables the application and instance of the application to be identifiable. Every instance of an application must have a unique name.\n[...]\n```\napiVersion:\n[...]\n/v1\n[...]\nkind: Deployment\n[...]\nmetadata:\n  labels:\n[...]\n.kubernetes.io\n[...]\n: wordpress-abcxyz\n[...]\n: \"4.9.4\"\n    app\n[...]\nkubernetes.io\n[...]\nby: Helm\n    app.kubernetes.io\n[...]\ncomponent: server\n[...]\n.kubernetes.io\n[...]\nof: wordpress\n[...]\napiVersion: apps/v1\n[...]\nkind: StatefulSet\n[...]\nmetadata:\n  labels:\n    app.kubernetes.io/\n[...]\napp.kubernetes.io/instance: mysql-abcxyz\n    app.kubernetes.io/version: \"5.7.21\"\n    app.kubernetes.io/managed-by: Helm\n    app.kubernetes.io/component: database\n    app.kubernetes.io\n[...]\napp.kubernetes.io/version:\n[...]\n5.7.21\n[...]\napp.kubernetes\n\n---\n\nTitle: Objects In Kubernetes | Kubernetes\nURL: https://kubernetes.io/docs/concepts/overview/working-with-objects/_print/\nPublished: 2025-11-24T21:22:29.000Z\nAuthor: N/A\nHighlights:\nIn the following examples, the`app` label is included for convenience in manual queries and simple CLI usage. The`app.kubernetes.io/name` label follows the recommended Kubernetes labeling conventions and is better suited for tooling and automation.\n[...]\nShared labels and annotations share a common prefix:`app.kubernetes.io`. Labels without a prefix are private to users. The shared prefix ensures that shared labels do not interfere with custom user labels.\n[...]\n| Key | Description | Example | Type |\n| --- | --- | --- | --- |\n| `app.kubernetes.io/name` | The name of the application | `mysql` | string |\n| `app.kubernetes.io/instance` | A unique name identifying the instance of an application | `mysql-abcxyz` | string |\n| `app.kubernetes.io/version` | The current version of the application (e.g., a SemVer 1.0, revision hash, etc.) | `5.7.21` | string |\n| `app.kubernetes.io/component` | The component within the architecture | `database` | string |\n| `app.kubernetes.io/part-of` | The name of a higher level application this one is part of | `wordpress` | string |\n| `app.kubernetes.io/managed-by` | The tool being used to manage the operation of an application | `Helm` | string |\n[...]\nmetadata:\n  labels:\n[...]\nThe name of an\n[...]\nare recorded separately. For example, WordPress has a`app.kubernetes.io/name` of\n[...]\nwordpress` while it has an\n[...]\nname, represented as`\n[...]\n.kubernetes.io/instance` with a value of`wordpress-abcxyz`. This enables the\n[...]\nof the application to be identifiable. Every\n[...]\nmust have a unique name\n[...]\napiVersion: apps/v1\nkind: Deployment\n[...]\nmetadata:\n  labels:\n    app.kubernetes.io/name: wordpress\n    app.kubernetes.io/instance: wordpress-abcxyz\n    app.kubernetes.io/version: \"4.9.4\"\n    app.kubernetes.io/managed-by: Helm\n    app.kubernetes.io/component: server\n    app.kubernetes.io/\n[...]\n-of: wordpress\n[...]\nmetadata:\n[...]\n:\n    app.kubernetes.io/\n[...]\napp.kubernetes.io/\n[...]\n-abcxyz\n[...]\nversion: \"5.7","metadata":{"truncated":false},"title":"","time":{"start":1777014317387,"end":1777014319143},"attachments":[]},"id":"prt_dbe4ea142001859CQBCfOsQYXM","sessionID":"ses_241d9f7b3ffeMqi0Lc2w61CcA3","messageID":"msg_dbe4e73a2001uTqJa28o1GX35E"}}
